						<h1>Part 1: Mobile Cross-Platform Fundamentals</h1>
						<div>
							There are three main devices that developers use to build mobile apps, they are Android, IOS and Windows Phone.  Which one should we choose?
							According to <a target="_blank" href="http://www.idc.com/prodserv/smartphone-os-market-share.jsp">http://www.idc.com/prodserv/smartphone-os-market-share.jsp</a>,  Android dominated the market with an 82.8% share in 2015 with IOS behind with 13.9% share and Windows Phone with 2.6%.
						</div>
						<br/>
						<div style="text-align: justify">
							Having this information helps us determine which platform we want to put or focus in and then we can research why the other platforms are not as popular.  Below is a table of the three most popular platforms and the programming languages and software used to create an mobile app.
						</div>
						<br />
						<div class="table-responsive">
							<table class="table .table-hover">
								<tr>
									<th>
										Operating System
									</th>
									<th>
										Programming Language Used
									</th>
									<th>
										Software Used
									</th>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td>
										Android
									</td>
									<td>
										Java
									</td>
									<td>
										IntelliJ IDEA, Elipse, Android Studio
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td>
										IOS (IPhone Operating System)
									</td>
									<td>
										Objective-C or Swift
									</td>
									<td>
										XCode IDE or Jet Brains AppCode
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td>
										Windows
									</td>
									<td>
										C#
									</td>
									<td>
