									</td>
								</tr>
							</table>
						</div>

						<div style="text-align: justify">
							As a developer, if you wanted to create mobile apps for Android you will have to learn the Java programming language.
							Let's say that there is a need for the Android app to go on a IOS phone, then now we have to learn Objective-C or Swift and spend time learning the language and transferring all the logic over.  What if there is a way to develop one make with one programming language?							
						</div>
						<br />
						<div style="text-align: justify">
							This is what cross-platform is all about where we can build one app that runs on all Operating Systems and fortunately there is an option to be able to do this.
							We present a product called <strong class="text-info"><a target="_blank" href="http://xamarin.com">Xamarin</a></strong>.  Xamarin is a product that allows developers to use the C# language to build one app one time that will run on all the three major mobile platforms.  There are a few drawbacks to consider but not something to worry much about.
							So the question now is when should we choose a programing language for a specific mobile device vs using a Cross-Platform tool such as Xamarin?
						</div>
						<br />
						<div>
							
							<h4>When to use Cross-Plaftform Xamarin</h4>
							<ul>
								<li>You need your app to run on multiple mobile platforms and love C#</li>
								<li>You or your team uses Visual Studio and do not want to use a new IDE</li>
							</ul>

							<br />
							<h4>When to use the native programming languages</h4>
							<ul>
								<li>You have experience with the language</li>
								<li>Cost of Xamarin license is not cheap ($1000 per platform / per dev)</li>
							</ul>								
						</div>


